</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: [GIT PULL] x86 fixes</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">From</td><td class="rp" itemprop="author">Linus Torvalds &lt;&gt;</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody">On Mon, Aug 17, 2015 at 1:01 AM, Ingo Molnar &lt;mingo&#64;kernel.org&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Any objections against removing all of math-emu in v4.3? This would simplify the<br />&gt; FPU code in various places beyond math-emu/.<br /><br />Hmm. I guess we could just try. The fact that you argue that the FP<br />emulation likely hasn't worked for a few years is a pretty powerful<br />argument that nobody has cared. And if somebody does, and ends up<br />having a use case and willing to test, we can always re-animate the<br />zombie that is math emu support.<br /><br />Considering that we don't support the old i386 any more, the only chip<br />I know of that needs it is the i486sx. However, there are probably<br />several clone chips that did the "we're a 486" thing by adding the few<br />integer instructions but not doing a FPU. And there might well be<br />various embedded versions of the 486 that might even be in use still.<br />But afaik most distributions have required Pentium of P6-level<br />capabilities for some time, and I guess any existing old systems<br />aren't going to upgrade their kernels anyway.<br /><br />                      Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
